<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by Polliwogg on 08-22-2001 11:40 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">An intresting occurance at work yesterday prompts me to write this as a separate entry. I work in an ER as an RN....nope not a grand profession, but a good one all the same. I'm the guy that brings your bedpan when you gotta go. Probably pretty menial a task, unless YOU REALLY GOTTA GO, and then I become your best friend, LOL! Anyways, I divurge....hadda patient yesterday, guy in his mid-forties, having "the BIG ONE"....so in short, we save his life and....we start talking, and he's a EQ fanatic too! And a coupla of his friends drop by to visit and they're all EQ'er's too! Really wierd part? Everybody there was at least 44 y.o., and one guy was 56! Needless to say, I was surprised and relieved that I am not the oldest EQ player in America ( at 34)Makes me feel good to know that at least a few of the players I encounter in-game aren't really snot nosed 12 year olds ( they just talk that way!)It worked out well....he lived, is doing fine and I got a guild invite! Tre Cool, ya know? So how does that fit into this? Well, of course we talked about things outside the game that affect us in the game, and EQATLAS was mentioned. Everybody in the conversation admitted that they had referred to this site dozens, if not hundreds of times while playing. And we agreed that whatever price you needed to charge to continue churning out this site and maps would be well worth it to an avid player. PayPal was mentioned and other idea's too. What about a subscription? Set fee or sliding scale ( obviously, teens playing on Mom and dad's CC could be somewhat limited in what they could pay)Bottom line? Whatever you needed to charge to keep this site open, people would more than likely be willing to pay.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
